{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"56a8d244-ea58-4b2d-8a84-ce5911baf72d","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n**Why:** After a .NET SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may be pinned to versions that are incompatible with the new SDK. `dotnet workload update` downloads and installs the latest workload versions that match your current SDK.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** only *reinstalls* the same workload versions you already have — it fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer, SDK-compatible versions. It wouldn't help here.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still hit issues after updating, `dotnet workload list` will confirm which workloads are installed and their versions.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9679093c-42cb-4c9b-947d-78ed5ed8f991","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the installed SDK. This is what you want after a SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations, but does NOT update them to newer versions.\n\n\n- So after a .NET SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to run since it'll sync the workloads with the new SDK version.","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"77F4:1B9BC9:8195932:8FB6B54:69EABD7E"},"id":"bdedf009-5406-4e64-ab78-4f1aa2c47bd4","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:47:05.728Z","parentId":"ff6f8cb1-1538-465c-9425-1a993a27f9ba"}
